"""
MKT Context Commentary — Job chapters 39–41
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-job-39-41.py

Ch 39 (30v): YHWH's animal questions (part 2 of the first speech) — mountain goats,
    wild donkeys (onager/serremu in Mesopotamian texts), wild ox/aurochs (re'em;
    rimu in Akkadian as royal power symbol), ostrich (feathers = Egyptian Ma'at symbol),
    war horse (Bronze Age military technology), hawk migration, eagle.
Ch 40 (24v): YHWH's first challenge and Job's submission; second challenge;
    Behemoth = hippopotamus (Egyptian Set/Typhon connection, pharaonic hunt ritual,
    Taweret goddess; hippo as chaos-creature; YHWH made Behemoth with Job, v15);
    Jordan floodplain context; papyrus/reed marsh ecology.
Ch 41 (34v): Leviathan — the chaos-dragon of the deep; Ugaritic Lotan/Baal cycle;
    Mesopotamian Tiamat/Marduk; fire-breathing, scale armor, the boiling wake;
    king over all the sons of pride; YHWH as Leviathan's maker, not merely his conqueror.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "39": {
    "1": "<p>YHWH&rsquo;s second cycle of questions (which began at 38:31 with the astronomical questions) continues into the animal kingdom. The transition from inanimate phenomena (cosmology, meteorology) to living creatures follows a logical sequence: from creation&rsquo;s structure to creation&rsquo;s inhabitants. The opening question &mdash; &ldquo;Do you know when the mountain goats give birth?&rdquo; &mdash; sets the pattern for the animal section: not the exotic or the terrifying but the biologically specific. Mountain goats (<em>ya&rsquo;alei sela&rsquo;</em>, rock-goats) inhabit the limestone cliffs of the Judean desert and Transjordan; their birthing behavior in inaccessible terrain was beyond human observation.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The questions about watching the hinds (<em>ayalot</em>, female deer) in labor and counting the months of pregnancy reflect the ANE understanding of animal biology as divinely ordered. In Mesopotamian omens literature, the behavior of animals &mdash; their births, migrations, and unusual activities &mdash; was systematically catalogued as divine signs; the Babylonian series <em>Shumma alu</em> contains extensive records of animal behavior observations. But observing wild deer in labor required access to their remote habitats that humans did not have. YHWH asks Job: have you been there for the birth that no human witnesses?</p>",
    "3": "<p>The image of deer crouching, opening their womb, and sending forth their young reflects the biological reality of cervid parturition: deer give birth alone in secluded areas, and the fawn immediately attempts to stand and walk. The ancient world noted this behavior (Egyptian and Mesopotamian hunting texts describe deer and their young) but could not observe the act of birth itself. The divine knowledge of the hidden birth is the theological point: YHWH has been present at every birth in the wild that no human eye has seen.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The fawns becoming strong and going out into the open, not returning to their mothers (&ldquo;their young ones become strong; they grow up in the open; they go out and do not return to them&rdquo;) describes the rapid independence of ruminant young. Unlike human children who require extended parental dependence, or domestic animals that continue to live near humans, wild ungulates achieve independence quickly. The divine ordering of this developmental pattern &mdash; embedding independence-programming in the animal at birth &mdash; is beyond human design or even observation.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The wild donkey (<em>pere&rsquo;</em>) &mdash; the Asiatic wild ass or onager &mdash; was well known in the ancient Near East. In Mesopotamian texts, the onager (<em>serremu</em> in Akkadian) was celebrated for its speed (Sumerian literature: &ldquo;swift as the wind, like a shadow&rdquo;) and untamability. Ishmael was compared to a <em>pere&rsquo;</em> (Gen 16:12) as the paradigm of the person who lives outside settled society&rsquo;s constraints. YHWH&rsquo;s question &mdash; who set the wild donkey free, who loosed its bonds? &mdash; asks about the origin of the freedom that makes the onager undomesticatable: the freedom itself is a divine gift.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The wild donkey&rsquo;s home in the salt flats (<em>melechah</em>) and the Arabah (the Jordan Rift Valley/desert) places the animal in the marginal environments between the settled agricultural zone and the deep desert. The <em>melechah</em> is the salt-impregnated land where nothing grows (cf. Deut 29:23; Ps 107:34 where salt land is a curse), but the onager can survive there. In Mesopotamian geography, the Mesopotamian plains shaded into the desert steppes where the onager ranged; the animal marked the boundary of human civilization.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The wild donkey laughing at the city tumult (<em>yiskhaq lahamon qiryah</em>) and not hearing the driver&rsquo;s shout describes freedom as heard acoustically: the sounds of civilization &mdash; the crowded city, the taskmaster&rsquo;s shout &mdash; are sounds of human bondage. The onager lives beyond the reach of these sounds. In the ancient world, the city (<em>qiryah</em>) was the center of civilization, taxation, and control; to be beyond its sounds was to be beyond its jurisdiction. The driver&rsquo;s shout (<em>tsha&rsquo;at noges</em>) uses the vocabulary of slave-driving (cf. the Exodus <em>nagasim</em> who drove Israelite labor). The free donkey exists in a world without slavery.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The wild donkey&rsquo;s ranging of the mountains in search of pasture describes the actual ecological behavior of wild equids: they cover enormous distances in search of adequate grazing in marginal environments. The Mesopotamian hunting texts describe expeditions into the desert steppe to hunt onagers; the Assyrian royal hunt texts catalogue onager hunts as demonstrations of royal mastery over wild creation. But no human has placed the onager in the mountains or taught it to search for green pasture; it does so by the programming that YHWH built into its nature.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The wild ox (<em>re&rsquo;em</em>) is the aurochs (<em>Bos primigenius</em>), the massive wild ancestor of domestic cattle, which survived in the ancient Near East until the late ancient/medieval period (the last known aurochs died in Poland in 1627 CE). In Akkadian texts, the <em>rimu</em> (cognate of <em>re&rsquo;em</em>) was a symbol of royal and divine power: Mesopotamian kings compared themselves to the rimu for strength (the Sargon cylinder: &ldquo;strong as a wild bull&rdquo;); Assyrian palace sculptures depicted the rimu. Num 23:22 and 24:8 use the re&rsquo;em as a symbol of divine power (&ldquo;God is for them like the horns of the wild ox&rdquo;). The question &mdash; will the re&rsquo;em consent to serve you? &mdash; asks whether human power can yoke divine-symbol strength.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The impossibility of plowing with a wild ox &mdash; binding it in the furrow, following it through the valleys &mdash; makes the agricultural point precise: the re&rsquo;em&rsquo;s power is available in nature but not for human agricultural use. The ox that plowed fields in the ancient world was the domesticated descendant of the wild ox, selected and bred over millennia for tractability; the wild ancestor retained the original power but lost the tractability. YHWH&rsquo;s question asks whether Job can reverse this domestication history and harness raw undomesticated power.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Trusting the wild ox with great strength (<em>ki-rav koho</em>) and leaving your labor to it assumes a relationship of trust between human and animal that domestication creates and that wild animals resist. In the ancient world, the ox was the primary draft animal for heavy agricultural work (plowing, threshing, grinding). The ox that threshes grain (Deut 25:4: do not muzzle the threshing ox) represents the cooperative relationship between human agriculture and animal labor. YHWH&rsquo;s question asks whether this cooperation can be extended to the untameable wild ox.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The question whether the wild ox will bring the harvest home and gather it to the threshing floor presupposes a different kind of animal trust than merely using the animal for work: it asks about the animal as an agent that can be trusted with the completed product, not just the labor. The <em>goren</em> (threshing floor) was the essential post-harvest processing site; in ancient Israelite social life, the threshing floor was a public space for community activity (Ruth 3:2-7; 2 Sam 24:16-24). The question asks whether the re&rsquo;em can be trusted with what matters most: the completed harvest.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The ostrich (<em>renanim</em>, possibly related to the word for crying out/joyful shout; or <em>ya&rsquo;en</em> in v14) section is the most theologically unusual passage in the divine speeches: YHWH explicitly says he withheld wisdom from the ostrich and gave it no understanding (v17). The ostrich was known throughout the ancient world. In Egypt, the ostrich feather was the symbol of <em>Ma&rsquo;at</em> (cosmic justice/order), used to weigh the soul of the dead against the feather of truth; the ostrich&rsquo;s equal-length wing and body feathers made it the symbol of cosmic balance and justice. YHWH uses this symbol-of-justice animal to illustrate divinely designed limitation.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The ostrich abandoning her eggs in the dust (<em>ta&rsquo;azov la&rsquo;aretz beytseha</em>) describes the ostrich&rsquo;s unusual nesting behavior. The ostrich does not incubate eggs by sitting on them like most birds; she buries them in sand and allows solar warmth to incubate them, with the male guarding the nest. To an ancient observer without biological knowledge, this appeared to be maternal abandonment &mdash; leaving eggs in the dust, apparently unprotected. The apparent cruelty of the behavior raised theological questions: has the ostrich violated the creation order that gives every creature appropriate care for its young?</p>",
    "15": "<p>The danger of the eggs being trampled by foot or broken by wild beasts was a real ecological hazard for ground-nesting birds. The description of the eggs being forgotten without awareness that a foot might crush them (<em>vattishkah ki regel tamushena</em>) makes the ostrich&rsquo;s carelessness seem extreme. In ancient Egyptian religious practice, the ostrich egg was a symbol of potential life; ostrich eggs were sometimes placed in tombs as symbols of renewal. The contrast between the ostrich egg as symbol (life and renewal) and the ostrich as parent (apparent indifference to the egg) is theologically provocative.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The description of the ostrich&rsquo;s young as not her own (<em>lehaqshikhah levanehah kilo&rsquo;)</em>) &mdash; hardening herself against them &mdash; uses the vocabulary of emotional detachment that is the supreme parental violation in the OT. Isa 49:15: &ldquo;Can a woman forget her nursing child, that she should have no compassion on the son of her womb?&rdquo; The question is rhetorical: the mother&rsquo;s attachment to her infant is the gold standard of attachment. The ostrich&rsquo;s apparent lack of this attachment is theologically coded as extreme. Yet YHWH made her this way.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The explicit statement that God did not give the ostrich wisdom (<em>ki nishshah &rsquo;eloha hokhmah</em>) and did not allot her understanding (<em>bilah hahliq binah</em>) is the most direct statement in the divine speeches that creation contains designed limitations. This is a significant theological move: YHWH does not claim that the ostrich is wise or that her apparent foolishness is secretly wise; he simply acknowledges that she was made without the capacity for wisdom in the specific area of protective parenting. The diversity of creation includes diversity of cognitive capacity, all by divine design.</p>",
    "18": "<p>But when the ostrich flaps her wings and runs (<em>be&rsquo;et tomerih lamerom</em>), she laughs at the horse and rider. The ostrich is the fastest land bird, capable of reaching 45mph; an ancient horse was slower. The compensation pattern &mdash; designed limitation in one area (parental wisdom) with extraordinary ability in another (speed) &mdash; is the theological point. The divine design of each creature includes both its limitations and its excellences; the question &ldquo;why did God give the ostrich no wisdom?&rdquo; is answered by &ldquo;because he gave her instead the ability to outrun the best technology of human warfare.&rdquo;</p>",
    "19": "<p>The war horse description is the divine speeches&rsquo; most extended single-animal passage (vv19&ndash;25). The horse (<em>sus</em>) was the premier military technology of the Late Bronze and Iron Ages; its combination with the chariot transformed ancient warfare from the Middle Bronze Age onward. The horse was not native to Canaan; it was introduced from the Central Asian steppes (modern Ukraine/Kazakhstan) ca. 3000 BCE, entering Egypt and the Levant in the Hyksos period (ca. 1650&ndash;1550 BCE). YHWH asks: did you clothe the horse&rsquo;s neck with its thunder (<em>ra&rsquo;amah</em>)? The thunder-neck is the arched, powerful neck of the stallion in full gallop, which ancient observers compared to rolling thunder.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The horse &ldquo;leaping like a locust&rdquo; (<em>haterish&rsquo;enu ka&rsquo;arbeh</em>) and its majestic snorting (<em>hodoh yir&rsquo;ah</em>) as terror uses two ANE comparisons: the locust swarm (the most feared agricultural catastrophe in the ancient Near East; locusts moving like a wall represented unstoppable destructive force, cf. Joel 2:1&ndash;11) and the <em>hod</em> (splendor/majesty) of the horse as an object of awe. Assyrian royal hunts depicted the horse as both beautiful and terrifying; the war horse in Assyrian palace reliefs is shown with flaring nostrils and arched neck in the precise posture YHWH describes.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The horse pawing in the valley (<em>yehperu va&rsquo;emeq vayasis bekoah</em>), exulting in strength, going out to meet weapons describes the pre-battle psychology of the trained war horse. Ancient cavalry and chariot horses were trained specifically to not flee from the sensory inputs of battle: the noise, the smell of blood, the chaos. In Mesopotamian military training texts, the horse-trainer (<em>sa-si-su</em>) trained horses through graduated exposure to noise and confusion. The psychological training of the war horse to face battle rather than flee it was one of antiquity&rsquo;s great achievements of animal domestication. YHWH asks: did you build this into the horse?</p>",
    "22": "<p>The horse &ldquo;laughing at fear&rdquo; and &ldquo;not dismayed&rdquo; (<em>yiskhaq lepahad velo-yehat</em>) continues the laughing (<em>sahaq</em>) vocabulary used for the wild donkey (v7: laughing at the city tumult). The courageous animal&rsquo;s fearlessness before things that terrify humans is a recurring theme in the divine speeches: wild freedom and fearlessness are characteristics built into certain animals that contrast with human vulnerability. The horse that does not shy from battle is the trained animal complement to the wild donkey that does not submit to human control; both represent forms of animal excellence that exceed human capacity.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The military equipment clashing against the horse &mdash; the quiver (<em>ashpah</em>), the glittering spear (<em>lahat hanit</em>), and the javelin (<em>kidon</em>) &mdash; is precise military vocabulary. The quiver contained arrows shot at the horse; the spear was the primary close-combat weapon; the <em>kidon</em> was the short throwing-javelin of ancient infantry. The Philistine champion Goliath carried a <em>kidon</em> (1 Sam 17:6,45). The three weapons represent the main threats to a cavalry horse in ancient battle; YHWH describes the horse as absorbing all of these without fleeing.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The horse swallowing the ground with fury and fierceness (<em>bere&rsquo;ash veragaz yegameh ha&rsquo;aretz</em>) uses the ground-consuming metaphor for the horse&rsquo;s gallop at full speed. The sound of the battle trumpet (<em>shofar</em>) triggers rather than deters the war horse: it signals the charge. In ancient armies, the <em>shofar</em> was the command-and-control signal (cf. Num 10:1&ndash;10: silver trumpets for military and liturgical commands; Judg 7:16&ndash;22: Gideon&rsquo;s trumpet signal). The war horse that responds to the trumpet by charging rather than fleeing represents the pinnacle of military animal training &mdash; a behavioral programming beyond human teaching alone.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The horse saying &ldquo;Ha!&rdquo; at the sound of the trumpet and smelling the battle from afar (<em>verishon milhama raah vero&rsquo;am sareyim uteri&rsquo;ah</em>) describes the war horse&rsquo;s sensory engagement with combat from a distance. Ancient horse psychology includes the ability to detect the smell of blood, gunpowder (in later periods), and battle-stress pheromones from far away. The thunder of captains (<em>ra&rsquo;am shareyim</em>) and the war-cry (<em>teri&rsquo;ah</em>) are the sounds that mobilize the trained horse. The divine question embedded in this extended description: who designed the horse to experience battle not as threat but as summons?</p>",
    "26": "<p>The hawk&rsquo;s spreading of wings toward the south (<em>hayeretz minbinatkha ya&rsquo;of nets</em>) refers to bird migration &mdash; one of the most mysterious natural phenomena of the ancient world. The seasonal disappearance and reappearance of migratory birds was observed but not understood; ancient natural historians knew that certain birds flew south for winter but did not know where they went or how they found their way. Jer 8:7: &ldquo;even the stork in the heavens knows her times, and the turtledove, swallow, and crane keep the time of their migration.&rdquo; The hawk&rsquo;s migration is presented as a divine endowment of navigational wisdom that Job neither possesses nor understands.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The eagle&rsquo;s mounting up and making its nest on high (<em>al-pika yagbia nesher</em>) asks whether Job commands the eagle to soar and nest on high crags. The eagle (<em>nesher</em>, which may include both the Golden Eagle and the Griffon Vulture in biblical usage) nests on inaccessible cliff faces throughout the Levant. Ps 103:5: &ldquo;who satisfies you with good, so that your youth is renewed like the eagle&rsquo;s.&rdquo; Isa 40:31: &ldquo;but they who wait for the LORD shall renew their strength; they shall mount up with wings like eagles.&rdquo; The eagle&rsquo;s height is both literal (highest nesting of any bird) and symbolic (the supreme emblem of divine perspective).</p>",
    "28": "<p>The eagle&rsquo;s dwelling and lodging on a cliff, on the rocky crag and stronghold (<em>al-shen-sela&rsquo; veloda&rsquo;</em>) describes the specific nesting ecology of cliff-nesting raptors. The Griffon Vulture and Golden Eagle of the Levant nest on south-facing limestone cliffs where the thermal updrafts allow effortless soaring. In ancient Israel, the eagle&rsquo;s nest on inaccessible crags was the paradigm of security and unreachability (Obad 4: &ldquo;though you soar aloft like the eagle, though your nest is set among the stars, from there I will bring you down&rdquo;). The divine provision of inaccessible nesting sites for the eagle maintains its wild independence from human access.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The eagle whose eyes spy prey from afar (<em>mishham yehappes &rsquo;okhel lemerhoq eneyhav yairu</em>) describes one of the most remarkable visual acuities in the animal kingdom. Eagles have approximately 4&ndash;8x human visual acuity; they can spot a rabbit or hare from 2 miles away. In the ancient world, this extraordinary visual capacity was known and celebrated in simile and metaphor. The divine question embedded here: who gave the eagle eyes that can see what human eyes cannot? The answer is the same as for all the divine questions: the Creator who endowed each creature with its specific capacities.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The eagle&rsquo;s young drinking blood and the carcass being where the slain are (<em>ufrahaiv ye&rsquo;alu dam uva&rsquo;asher hallelim sham hu&rsquo;</em>) closes the animal section with the cycle of life and death. Eagles and vultures feed on carcasses; in the ancient world, this was understood as part of the divine provision for the clean-up of the dead. The Mosaic Law distinguished between clean and unclean birds, placing eagles among the unclean (Lev 11:13) precisely because of their association with carrion. The ecological function of carrion-feeding birds in disposing of the dead was observed even if the full biological rationale was not understood. YHWH&rsquo;s question: did you design this system of life feeding on death?</p>"
  },
  "40": {
    "1": "<p>The structural transition at 40:1 marks the end of YHWH&rsquo;s first speech. The formula <em>vaya&rsquo;an YHWH et-&rsquo;iyyov</em> (YHWH answered/responded to Job) opens both speeches (38:1 and 40:6); its recurrence here marks a clear formal division in the divine speeches into two rounds. The first speech (38:1&ndash;40:5) covered cosmology, meteorology, and zoology; the second speech (40:6&ndash;41:34) will focus on the two great chaos-creatures: Behemoth and Leviathan. The legal vocabulary (<em>&rsquo;anah</em>, answer/respond) frames the entire divine discourse as YHWH&rsquo;s formal legal reply to Job&rsquo;s petition.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The challenge &mdash; &ldquo;Shall a fault-finder contend with (<em>yariv</em>) Shaddai?&rdquo; &mdash; uses the legal-dispute vocabulary that has pervaded the book. The <em>riv</em> (legal complaint/lawsuit) is precisely what Job has threatened to bring against God (Job 13:3: &ldquo;I desire to argue my case with God&rdquo;; 23:4: &ldquo;I would lay my case before him&rdquo;). YHWH now formally invites the <em>riv</em>: let the one who argues with God answer! The <em>mokhiah</em> (reprover/fault-finder) who contends with God is the one who takes the role of legal challenger; YHWH accepts the challenge and immediately turns it back.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Job&rsquo;s response to YHWH (vv3&ndash;5) is the book&rsquo;s first verbal response from Job to the divine speeches. The brevity is striking: the man who filled 29+ chapters with sustained argument is reduced to two verses. The structural contrast between Job&rsquo;s speeches (multi-chapter, extensively argued) and his response to YHWH (four short phrases) is a formal demonstration of what the divine speeches have accomplished: not by refuting Job&rsquo;s arguments but by revealing a reality so vastly larger than the argumentative framework that the arguments become irrelevant.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;Behold, I am of small account (<em>qallotiy</em>); what shall I answer you? I lay my hand on my mouth&rdquo; &mdash; the hand-over-mouth gesture is the ANE posture of submission before divine authority. In Mesopotamian royal iconography, the devoted suppliant before the king raised a hand before the mouth in the gesture of reverent silence. In Ugaritic texts, human figures before the gods are depicted in similar postures. Isa 6:5: Isaiah&rsquo;s &ldquo;woe is me, I am undone&rdquo; at the throne-room vision; the prophet falls silent before divine holiness. Job&rsquo;s gesture enacts the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s principle: there is a time for every word and a time for silence (Prov 17:28: even a fool who keeps silent is considered wise).</p>",
    "5": "<p>&ldquo;I have spoken once, and I will not answer; twice, but I will proceed no further&rdquo; &mdash; the &ldquo;once&rdquo; and &ldquo;twice&rdquo; formula is a common ANE literary pattern for climactic emphasis: Ugaritic texts use the &ldquo;once&hellip;twice&rdquo; formula (Akkadian: <em>ishten&hellip;shinaateni</em>) in wisdom sayings; the biblical <em>x&hellip;x+1</em> formula appears in Prov 30:15&ndash;31 (the graded numerical sayings) and throughout Amos (1:3,6,9,11: &ldquo;for three transgressions and for four&rdquo;). Job&rsquo;s &ldquo;once/twice&rdquo; is not an exact count but the rhetorical formula for &ldquo;completely, definitively.&rdquo; He has said all he will say; the argument is closed on his side.</p>",
    "6": "<p>YHWH&rsquo;s second speech begins with the identical introduction as the first (38:1): &ldquo;Then the LORD spoke to Job out of the whirlwind.&rdquo; The <em>se&rsquo;arah</em> (whirlwind/storm) is the recognized form of theophanic appearance in the OT. Elijah was taken up in a whirlwind (2 Kgs 2:1,11); Ezekiel&rsquo;s inaugural vision came &ldquo;out of the north, a great cloud with brightness around it and fire flashing forth continually&rdquo; (Ezek 1:4). In Mesopotamian theology, the storm-god Enlil communicated through storms; the Akkadian noun <em>assatu</em> (storm-whirlwind) was associated with divine anger-manifestation. The deliberate repetition of 38:1 signals that Job&rsquo;s submission (vv3&ndash;5) has not ended the divine speech; YHWH has more to say.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The renewed command &mdash; &ldquo;Dress for action like a man; I will question you and you make it known to me&rdquo; &mdash; repeats 38:3 verbatim. The phrase <em>&rsquo;ezer na keggever</em> (gird your loins/dress for action like a <em>gever</em>) uses the <em>gever</em> (strong man/warrior) form of the word for man, not the ordinary <em>&rsquo;ish</em>. The military gesture of girding loins prepared a man for battle or strenuous action by pulling the long outer garment up and tucking it into a belt. Elijah girded his loins before running ahead of Ahab&rsquo;s chariot (1 Kgs 18:46); the Passover was eaten with loins girded (Exod 12:11). YHWH repeats his challenge: stand up and face what is about to come.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The second speech&rsquo;s challenge takes a different form from the cosmological questions: &ldquo;Will you even put me in the wrong? Will you condemn me that you may be in the right?&rdquo; This is the legal crux. Job&rsquo;s sustained argument for his own innocence has implied that if Job is innocent and God is allowing/causing his suffering, then God is in the wrong. YHWH names this implication directly: are you condemning me (<em>tarshe&rsquo;eni</em>) in order to justify yourself (<em>lema&rsquo;an titsdak</em>)? The judicial vocabulary is explicit: <em>rasha&rsquo;</em> (condemn as guilty) and <em>tsadaq</em> (vindicate/justify). The divine legal challenge is not &ldquo;stop asking questions&rdquo; but &ldquo;face the implications of what your legal claims require.&rdquo;</p>",
    "9": "<p>&ldquo;Have you an arm like God, and can you thunder with a voice like his?&rdquo; &mdash; the divine attributes of arm (<em>zero&rsquo;a</em>) and thunder (<em>ra&rsquo;am</em>) are the two primary expressions of divine power in ANE theology. The divine arm is the instrument of creation and military victory: Exod 15:16 (the arm of YHWH that redeems Israel); Isa 51:9 (the arm that cut Rahab in pieces). The divine thunder-voice is the storm-theophany: Ps 29 is a sustained meditation on YHWH&rsquo;s thunder as the voice that breaks cedars, shakes the wilderness, and strips forests. In Ugaritic theology, Baal&rsquo;s thunder was his voice; YHWH appropriates this attribute as his own.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The challenge to Job to &ldquo;deck yourself with majesty (<em>ga&rsquo;on</em>) and dignity (<em>gova</em>); clothe yourself with glory (<em>hod</em>) and splendor (<em>hadar</em>)&rdquo; uses the vocabulary of royal investiture. In the ancient world, kings were visibly distinguished from ordinary people by their garments, crowns, and insignia; the divine king was similarly clothed in cosmic garments. Ps 93:1: &ldquo;The LORD reigns; he is robed in majesty; the LORD is robed; he has put on strength as his belt.&rdquo; Ps 104:1&ndash;2: &ldquo;You are clothed with splendor and majesty, covering yourself with light as with a garment.&rdquo; YHWH challenges Job to don the divine royal costume &mdash; a challenge only one person in the book is in fact qualified to meet.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The challenge to pour out the overflowings of anger (<em>shophekhey evratekha</em>) and look on every proud one and abase him reflects the divine role as the one who humbles the proud. The theme of YHWH humbling the proud and lifting up the lowly (1 Sam 2:7&ndash;8; Ps 75:7; Prov 3:34; Isa 2:12&ndash;17) is one of the most consistent themes in OT theology. The proud ones (<em>ge&rsquo;im</em>) are those who assert themselves above their creaturely status; the divine response to human pride is humiliation. The challenge to Job: if you can do what God does &mdash; humble every proud one &mdash; then you are qualified to critique divine justice.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Treading down the wicked where they stand and hiding them in the dust together (<em>tehbem be&rsquo;afar yakhad</em>), binding their faces in the hidden place, is the complete execution of retributive justice against the proud and wicked. YHWH&rsquo;s rhetorical challenge is: if Job can execute justice by himself against all the wicked simultaneously, then Job&rsquo;s complaint that God has failed to do so would be self-refuting &mdash; Job himself would have proven that the task is within a being&rsquo;s power. The argument reveals the scale problem in Job&rsquo;s complaint: the cosmic administration of justice is not a task that admits of the simple standard Job has applied to it.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The description of hiding the proud in the dust and binding their faces in the hidden place uses the imagery of complete defeat and burial. In ANE warfare, the defeated were sometimes buried face-down as a mark of disgrace; the binding of the face was the posture of total submission. The &ldquo;hidden place&rdquo; (<em>batamuhn</em>, the place of concealment) may refer to the underworld/Sheol where the dead are hidden from the living. The entire challenge (vv10&ndash;14) amounts to: become God, execute universal perfect justice against all evil simultaneously, and then your criticism of God&rsquo;s administration of justice will be self-consistent.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The conditional promise &mdash; &ldquo;then will I also praise you to you that your own right hand can save you&rdquo; (<em>todeh lekha yeminekha toshia&rsquo; lakh</em>) &mdash; is the culminating irony of the second speech&rsquo;s opening challenge. If Job can execute perfect retributive justice against all the proud and wicked, then Job&rsquo;s own hand can save him. In the OT, the divine right hand is the instrument of salvation (Exod 15:6: &ldquo;your right hand, O LORD, glorious in power, your right hand, O LORD, shatters the enemy&rdquo;; Ps 20:6). The challenge implies its own answer: Job&rsquo;s right hand cannot execute justice against all evil; therefore it cannot save him; therefore he needs the divine right hand that can.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The transition to Behemoth (<em>behemat</em>) is introduced with the remarkable phrase <em>asher asiti immakh</em> &mdash; &ldquo;which I made with you.&rdquo; Behemoth was made with Job; both are creatures of the same Creator. This co-creaturely relationship is the frame for the description: YHWH is not simply describing a terrifying animal to humble Job but pointing to a co-creature whose existence Job has not considered. <strong>Behemoth</strong> is almost certainly the hippopotamus (<em>Hippopotamus amphibius</em>), the largest land animal in the ancient world familiar to Israelites through Egypt. Hippos lived in the Nile and in the lower Jordan River until the medieval period.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Behemoth&rsquo;s strength in his loins (<em>koho bemotnav</em>) and power in the muscles of his belly (<em>ve&rsquo;onov bishrirey vitno</em>) reflects the hippopotamus&rsquo;s actual physical characteristics: the hippo is the third-largest land animal on earth (after elephant and rhinoceros), weighing up to 3,000 kg, with enormous muscular power concentrated in its torso. In Egyptian religion, the hippopotamus had a complex mythological role: the male hippo was associated with Set, the god of chaos and disorder (a dangerous animal); the female hippo was represented as Taweret, the benevolent goddess of fertility and childbirth. The hippo was simultaneously a chaos-figure and a protective-deity figure.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Behemoth stiffening his tail like a cedar (&ldquo;he stiffens his tail like a cedar; the sinews of his thighs are knit together&rdquo;) is an anatomically precise description. The hippopotamus has a small but muscular tail which it wags to spread dung as territorial marking; the description of stiffening suggests the tail in its fully extended territorial display. The cedar comparison uses the tree associated with permanence, strength, and royal grandeur (Solomon&rsquo;s cedars of Lebanon; Ps 92:12: the righteous flourish like a cedar). The hippo&rsquo;s apparently incongruous small tail stiffened to cedar-like rigidity demonstrates the unexpected distribution of power in created creatures.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Behemoth&rsquo;s bones as bronze tubes (<em>atsamav afiqei nehusheh</em>) and his limbs like bars of iron (<em>geramav kemin barzel</em>) uses the metals of warfare as comparisons for biological structural strength. In the ancient world, bronze was the primary metal of weapons and armor (from ca. 3300 BCE); iron superseded it in the Iron Age (ca. 1200 BCE onward). The weapons-metal comparison for animal bone and limb strength frames the hippo in the vocabulary of military power &mdash; the thing humanity most prided itself on in the ancient world. The hippo&rsquo;s bones are weapons-grade; its strength exceeds manufactured military strength.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Behemoth as &ldquo;the first of God&rsquo;s works&rdquo; (<em>re&rsquo;shit darkhey &rsquo;el</em>) and &ldquo;made to rule over his companions&rdquo; uses creation-priority language. In ANE creation theology, the first-created held primacy; the Akkadian term for the first-created among gods or creatures denoted priority of dignity. YHWH&rsquo;s description places Behemoth at the head of the animal creation &mdash; first, greatest, made to be the chief. The &ldquo;one who made him can approach him with the sword&rdquo; (only the creator can threaten the first-creation) establishes the Creator-creature asymmetry as the fundamental relationship that governs Behemoth&rsquo;s place.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The mountains yielding food for Behemoth with all the wild animals playing nearby describes the ecological niche of the hippo in its riverine environment. Hippos graze at night on riverbank vegetation, consuming up to 35kg of grass per night; during daylight they rest in water. The mountains bringing tribute is hyperbolic for the abundant vegetation of the Nile and Jordan floodplains where hippos fed. The &ldquo;wild animals playing around him&rdquo; reflects the reality of hippo-dominated aquatic environments where other animals shared the water and banks with hippos.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Behemoth lying under lotus plants in the cover of the reeds and in the marsh (<em>tahat tse&rsquo;elim yishkav beseter qaneh ubitsah</em>) is a precise ecological description of hippopotamus habitat. The lotus (<em>tse&rsquo;el</em>, the Egyptian lotus or water lily) and the reed/papyrus (<em>qaneh</em>) were the characteristic plants of the Nile delta and its tributaries; papyrus marshes (<em>tsah</em>) were the hippo&rsquo;s natural concealment environment. In Egyptian art, the hippo is frequently depicted in papyrus swamps; Pharaoh Amenhotep III documented a royal hippo hunt in the papyrus swamps of the Fayum. Job&rsquo;s audience familiar with Egypt would recognize this habitat.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The shade of the lotus plants covering Behemoth and the willows of the brook surrounding him describes the concealment of the hippopotamus in its aquatic environment. The willow (<em>arvey nahal</em>, willows of the stream/brook) grows along watercourses throughout the Levant and Egypt; in Ps 137:2 the exiles hung their harps on the willows of Babylon. The natural canopy of lotus, reed, and willow over a resting hippopotamus creates an enclosure that gives even this enormous animal apparent invisibility. The theological point: YHWH designed concealment for the creature that needs no concealment &mdash; another example of divine provision beyond functional necessity.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Behemoth&rsquo;s confidence even when the Jordan surges into his mouth (<em>hen ya&rsquo;ashok nahar lo yahfoz</em>, the river rages but he is not frightened; he is secure though Jordan floods into his mouth) places the hippo in its Near Eastern context. The Jordan River&rsquo;s seasonal flooding (Josh 3:15: &ldquo;the Jordan overflows all its banks throughout the time of harvest&rdquo;) was the annual reality of the floodplain. Hippos were present in the lower Jordan Valley in biblical times; archaeological evidence confirms hippo bones in Jordan River deposits. The hippo&rsquo;s physiological design &mdash; semi-aquatic, with eyes and nostrils on top of the skull for surface breathing while submerged &mdash; makes flooding an irrelevance rather than a threat.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The rhetorical question &mdash; can one take Behemoth when he is on watch, pierce his nose with a snare? &mdash; establishes the impossibility of human domination over Behemoth. The hippo hunt was one of pharaoh&rsquo;s prerogatives in Egypt; special religious and political significance attached to the royal hippo hunt (the ritual defeat of Set/chaos-in-hippo-form by the pharaoh represented cosmic order triumphing over chaos). But ordinary human hunters could not take the hippo. The divine question to Job: can <em>you</em> catch Behemoth? The implied answer is no; only the Creator who made him can approach him (v19). The Creator&rsquo;s unique access to the creature he made is the theological point.</p>"
  },
  "41": {
    "1": "<p>The Leviathan description is the longest single-animal passage in the Bible and the climax of both divine speeches. <strong>Leviathan</strong> (<em>liwyatan</em>) is the sea-dragon/chaos-monster whose name and mythology are shared across the ancient Near East. In the <strong>Ugaritic Baal cycle</strong> from Ras Shamra (14th&ndash;12th c. BCE), Baal&rsquo;s enemy is <em>Lotan</em> (&ldquo;Twisting One&rdquo;), described as &ldquo;the Twisting Serpent&rdquo; (<em>btn &lsquo;qltn</em>) and &ldquo;the Powerful One with Seven Heads.&rdquo; The opening question &mdash; can you draw out Leviathan with a hook? &mdash; asks whether Job can catch the chaos-monster with the equipment of an ordinary fisherman. The contrast between the hook-and-line of fishing and the cosmic scale of Leviathan is deliberate.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The image of pressing down Leviathan&rsquo;s tongue with a cord (<em>uve&rsquo;avot tasheqa leshonov</em>) and putting a rope in its nose (v2) continues the fishing/trapping imagery. In ancient Egypt, pharaonic hippopotamus hunts used ropes and nets; in Mesopotamia, the hunt of wild beasts required elaborate trapping equipment described in cuneiform hunting texts. The domestication/capture of dangerous wild animals required equipment vastly exceeding a single person&rsquo;s capability. YHWH&rsquo;s questions multiply the impossibility: not just catching but restraining the tongue (the fire-breathing organ, described in v18&ndash;21) by a cord.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The rhetorical questions about Leviathan making supplications to Job (<em>hayarbe &rsquo;eleycha tahanunim</em>) and speaking soft words reflect the absolute power differential. In the ancient court, suppliants addressed the powerful in the posture of submission: kneeling, bowing, speaking softly to invoke mercy. The question is: would Leviathan adopt the posture of a suppliant before Job? The absurdity of the chaos-dragon making supplication to a human being reveals the absurdity of Job&rsquo;s implicit claim to have authority over the structure of creation.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The covenant with Leviathan (&ldquo;will he make a covenant with you to take him as your servant forever?&rdquo;) uses the most significant legal-political institution of the ancient world. The covenant (<em>berit</em>) established a formal, binding relationship between parties of unequal power in the ancient Near East: the suzerain-vassal treaty (the Hittite treaty texts are the clearest examples) defined the relationship between an overlord and a dependent. To make Leviathan your <em>eved &rsquo;olam</em> (permanent servant) would be to achieve the ultimate lordship over the chaos-principle itself. YHWH asks: can you do this?</p>",
    "5": "<p>Playing with Leviathan as a bird and putting it on a leash for your young girls continues the domestication imagery with increasing absurdity: from fishing (v1) to trapping (v2) to covenant servanthood (v4) to pet-bird (v5). In the ancient world, exotic animals were kept as pets and status symbols by the wealthy: Assyrian kings kept lions, bears, and other dangerous animals in palace menageries; Solomon&rsquo;s ships brought exotic animals (1 Kgs 10:22: apes and peacocks). But Leviathan as a pet bird &mdash; domesticated and leashed for children to play with &mdash; reduces the absurdity to its maximum. The progressive escalation from fishing to pet-leash tracks the impossibility through ascending social registers.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The commercial question &mdash; will traders bargain over Leviathan and divide it among merchants? &mdash; frames the chaos-dragon in the commercial economy of the ancient Near East. Sea creatures were commodities: fish were traded, dried, and sold throughout the ancient world (Nehemiah 13:16: Tyrians sold fish in Jerusalem). The question of who gets which portion (<em>yeheltsu &rsquo;alav hovarim?</em>) is the language of commercial division. But Leviathan cannot be divided for commerce: its existence as the chaos-principle transcends any commodity system. The very notion of merchandising the primordial sea-monster reveals the inadequacy of human commercial categories to encompass it.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The questions about filling Leviathan&rsquo;s skin with harpoons (<em>harpunim</em>) and his head with fishing spears (<em>tsaley dagah</em>) use the vocabulary of ancient sea-hunting. The <em>harpun</em> is the barbed spear-weapon used for large fish and sea mammals; the same word appears in Hebrew inscriptions from the ancient maritime world. In ancient Mediterranean sea-hunting, harpooning was used for tuna, swordfish, and eventually whales. The scale of Leviathan exceeds any creature that could be brought down by such equipment; no accumulation of harpoons and spears could penetrate the armor described in vv15&ndash;17.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&ldquo;Lay your hand on him; remember the battle &mdash; you will not do it again!&rdquo; &mdash; this verse contains the most direct address to Job in the animal descriptions. The invitation to try touching Leviathan and the warning that the memory of what happens will prevent any repetition is the voice of practical experience warning against foolishness. In Mesopotamian literature, the hero who faces the chaos-monster does so with divine backing (Marduk against Tiamat in the Enuma Elish; Baal against Yam in the Ugaritic texts); no human hero unilaterally defeats the chaos-dragon. The tacit comparison: Job&rsquo;s solo legal challenge against God is structurally analogous to fighting Leviathan alone.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The hope of one who stands against Leviathan being false (<em>hen tohalat &rsquo;okhzah</em>) and being cast down at the very sight of him uses the ANE category of hope that is fraudulent &mdash; hope that the experience of reality exposes as impossible. In Ps 39:7 Job uses similar vocabulary about human hope; in Lamentations the destroyed Jerusalem sits with disappointed hope as a central theme. The specific detail of being cast down at the mere sight (<em>mima&rsquo;ehu</em>) before even engaging describes the overwhelming effect of encountering the full scale of something that one had approached with inadequate mental preparation.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&ldquo;No one is fierce enough to rouse him; who then is he who can stand before me?&rdquo; &mdash; the move from Leviathan&rsquo;s invincibility to divine invincibility is the logical pivot of the entire animal section. If no human is fierce enough to rouse the chaos-dragon (and Job 3:8 shows that only specialist cursers can attempt even this), then a fortiori no human can stand before the Creator who made the chaos-dragon and set its limits. The argument from Leviathan to YHWH uses the same <em>qal vahomer</em> structure that runs through the entire divine speeches.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&ldquo;Who has given to me, that I should repay him? Whatever is under the whole heaven is mine&rdquo; &mdash; this verse expresses the doctrine of divine aseity in its most absolute form: God owes nothing to anyone because everything belongs to God. In legal terms, a <em>riv</em> (lawsuit) requires that the plaintiff have a legitimate claim against the defendant &mdash; something owed and not paid. YHWH&rsquo;s declaration that nothing can be given to him (because he already owns everything) removes the legal basis for Job&rsquo;s claim: there is no prior debt that God owes Job, and therefore no legal grievance. The theological point is not that God is unconcerned with justice but that the legal framework Job has been trying to use is inapplicable to the Creator-creature relationship.</p>",
    "12": "<p>YHWH&rsquo;s declaration that he will not keep silence about Leviathan&rsquo;s limbs or his mighty strength or his graceful frame (<em>velo &rsquo;aharis badaiv omegevorat erkho vegikhas darkhov</em>) signals the transition to the extended physical description of vv13&ndash;34. The vocabulary of Leviathan&rsquo;s &ldquo;graceful frame&rdquo; (<em>erko</em>, his arrayed/graceful design) presents the chaos-dragon not as ugly or repulsive but as having a designed elegance: even the chaos-principle is artfully made. In Ugaritic art, Lotan/Leviathan is depicted as a coiled serpent with aesthetic coherence; Mesopotamian chaos-creatures (Tiamat, Anzu) are depicted with terrifying grandeur rather than shapeless ugliness.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The question &mdash; who can strip off Leviathan&rsquo;s outer garment, and who can come near him with a double bridle? &mdash; begins the armor description. The &ldquo;outer garment&rdquo; (<em>penei livushaw</em>, the surface/face of his clothing) is the first image for Leviathan&rsquo;s impenetrable exterior. In ANE armor technology, the double bridle (<em>refes kiphlayim</em>, double fence/curb-bit) was the control mechanism for chariot horses; to put a double bridle on Leviathan would be to domesticate it to chariot use &mdash; an impossibility that parallels the wild-ox-plowing question of 39:10&ndash;12.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Leviathan&rsquo;s doors of his face (<em>daltot panav</em>) and his teeth as terror surround (<em>gadrot shinav &rsquo;emah</em>) describe the great mouth as a guarded gate. In ancient ANE military architecture, the gate was the most defended point of a city: the double gates, the guardrooms, the towers on either side. Leviathan&rsquo;s jaw is framed as an impregnable gate-system; its teeth are the terrors stationed at the gate. In Mesopotamian underworld mythology, the gates of Irkalla (the underworld) were guarded and had to be opened by key-keepers (the Descent of Ishtar: &ldquo;gatekeeper, open the gate for me&rdquo;). Leviathan&rsquo;s face-gates connect the sea-dragon to the underworld gate-imagery.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Leviathan&rsquo;s back is made of rows of shields (<em>gaavah maghinnot</em>), shut up closely as with a seal (<em>sarur tsotam tsarum</em>). The shields (<em>maginnim</em>) that form Leviathan&rsquo;s back-armor use the vocabulary of military defensive equipment: the <em>magen</em> (shield) was the primary defensive weapon of ancient infantry. Assyrian reliefs depict soldiers with large rectangular shields (the Assyrian body-shield) and smaller round shields; YHWH&rsquo;s description of Leviathan&rsquo;s scales as overlapping shields in lock-step formation uses this military imagery. The seal (<em>hotem</em>) that closes a document without gap is here used for the seamless interlocking of scales: as tightly closed as a royal seal on a document.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The scales being so close to one another that no air can pass between them (<em>ehad be&rsquo;ehad yigashu veru&rsquo;ah lo-yavo veyneyhem</em>) is a description of the functional impenetrability of overlapping plate-armor. In ancient armor technology, the goal of scale armor or plate armor was to eliminate gaps; a sword could penetrate through gaps between scales. The description of Leviathan&rsquo;s scale-armor as airtight &mdash; not just without gaps but without even air-space between scales &mdash; describes an ideal armor that exceeds any human manufacture. This is the cosmological warfare point: the chaos-monster is armored beyond human weapons technology.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The scales being joined to each other, interlocked, not separated (<em>ishu dobuqot beze elo yitparadhu</em>) continues the armor description with the vocabulary of structural cohesion. In Hebrew, <em>dabaq</em> (to cling, stick, join) is the word used for the covenant bonding of Ruth to Naomi (Ruth 1:14), for the marriage union of Gen 2:24 (&ldquo;a man shall leave his father and his mother and hold fast to his wife&rdquo;), and for human devotion to God (Deut 10:20; Josh 22:5). The word&rsquo;s use for Leviathan&rsquo;s unbreakable scale-interlocking takes the strongest OT bonding-vocabulary and applies it to physical armor construction.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Leviathan&rsquo;s sneezings flash forth light (<em>atishot yafi negoho</em>) and his eyes are like the eyelids of the dawn (<em>veyenav ke&rsquo;apappey shahar</em>). The eyes-of-dawn metaphor uses the poetic description of the first light appearing on the horizon before sunrise as an image of intense, illuminating brilliance. Job 3:9 used the same <em>&rsquo;apappey shahar</em> in the birthday curse (let the eyelids of the dawn be withheld from that night). The fire-breathing description begins here: what appears as sneezings (physiological, mundane) produces supernatural light &mdash; a deliberate contrast between biological process and cosmic effect.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Torches of fire flaming from Leviathan&rsquo;s mouth (<em>mipiv lapidim yehalokhu kidudey &rsquo;esh yitmalathu</em>) and sparks of fire leaping from it describe the fire-breathing capacity that became the central feature of the dragon/chaos-monster in later world mythology. In ancient Near Eastern iconography, fire-breathing creatures appear in Mesopotamian art: the snake-dragon (<em>mushushu</em>) of Marduk is depicted breathing fire in some representations; the Anzu bird breathed devastating wind. In Ugaritic mythology, Baal&rsquo;s defeat of Yam/Lotan included descriptions of cosmic power. The physiological fire-breathing connects Leviathan to the thunderstorm whose lightning-bolts are the divine fire-weapons (Ps 18:12&ndash;14: YHWH shoots fire-arrows/lightning).</p>",
    "20": "<p>Smoke going forth from Leviathan&rsquo;s nostrils as from a boiling pot and burning rushes (<em>menapav yetse &rsquo;shan kesirhafuah ve&rsquo;agemon</em>) uses the domestic cauldron (<em>sir</em>, the cooking pot) as comparison for the scale of the smoke-production. The cooking pot over a fire of rushes (<em>&rsquo;agamon</em>, bulrush/reeds &mdash; the same reeds of the Nile marshes) was the most intense-heat cooking method of the ancient world; rushes burned hot and fast. The smoke from Leviathan&rsquo;s nostrils filling the sky like a cauldron&rsquo;s steam is the inverse of the divine smoke at Sinai (Exod 19:18: &ldquo;Mount Sinai was wrapped in smoke because the LORD had descended on it in fire; the smoke of it went up like the smoke of a kiln&rdquo;).</p>",
    "21": "<p>Leviathan&rsquo;s breath setting coals ablaze and a flame coming from his mouth uses the same fire-vocabulary as the description of YHWH&rsquo;s power in the Psalter: Ps 18:8 (&ldquo;smoke went up from his nostrils and devouring fire from his mouth; glowing coals flamed forth from him&rdquo;). The parallel between the divine fire-description and the Leviathan fire-description is deliberate: Leviathan&rsquo;s fire-breathing is the creature-level analog of YHWH&rsquo;s theophanic fire. As Behemoth&rsquo;s bone-strength was compared to weapons-metal, Leviathan&rsquo;s fire-breathing is compared to the fire that accompanies divine theophany.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Strength dwelling in Leviathan&rsquo;s neck (<em>vegavo yasun &rsquo;oz</em>) and before him dances terror (<em>velefanav teduts deava</em>) introduces the battle-encounter imagery. The neck as the locus of strength is consistent with the war-horse description (39:19: the neck clothed with thunder) and with ancient iconography where the powerful neck of the bull, the lion, and the chariot horse expressed physical dominance. The personification of terror (<em>deava</em>) as dancing (<em>teduts</em>) before Leviathan is a remarkable image: terror is not merely the emotion felt by those who face the chaos-dragon; it is a personified attendant that precedes him like a herald.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The folds of his flesh clinging together (<em>mapelay besaro devequm yatsuq &rsquo;alav</em>), hard as cast metal, not moving &mdash; uses metalworking vocabulary for biological structure. <em>Yatsaq</em> (to pour/cast metal) is the verb for bronze and gold casting (1 Kgs 7:24: cast bronze; Exod 25:12: cast gold rings). The claim that Leviathan&rsquo;s flesh is as hard and immovable as cast metal makes the same weapons-grade comparison as the Behemoth bone-description (40:18). The ancient world&rsquo;s hardest material was cast bronze; describing flesh that is as immovable as cast metal describes armor that is simultaneously biological and metallurgical &mdash; unachievable by human manufacture.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Leviathan&rsquo;s heart being cast hard as a stone (<em>libo yatsuk ke&rsquo;even</em>) and hard as the lower millstone (<em>veyutsat ketahat rekhayyim</em>) uses two hardness comparisons: the stone (the standard ancient measure of absolute hardness for biological tissues) and the lower millstone (<em>pelekh rekhev</em>). The millstone was made of basalt, the hardest common stone available in the Levant; the lower millstone bore the weight of the grain and the rotating upper stone. &ldquo;As hard as the lower millstone&rdquo; is the hardness comparison that emphasizes not just hardness but load-bearing hardness. Leviathan&rsquo;s heart is not merely stone-hard; it is structurally reinforced stone-hard.</p>",
    "25": "<p>When Leviathan raises himself, the mighty are afraid (<em>mishi&rsquo;to yeguhu &rsquo;elim</em>) and at his crashing they are bewildered (<em>mishivarim yithhatau</em>). The mighty ones (<em>&rsquo;elim</em>) who fear Leviathan are probably the divine beings/heavenly council (the same <em>bene ha-&rsquo;elohim</em> of the prologue) rather than human warriors; the chaos-dragon terrifies even the divine court. In Ugaritic texts, El and the divine assembly were described as shaking with fear before the power of Yam/Lotan before Baal fought him; the chaos-dragon&rsquo;s threat preceded Baal&rsquo;s heroic combat. YHWH&rsquo;s description positions Leviathan as a creature so awesome that even divine beings are terrified.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The sword that reaches Leviathan cannot avail, nor the spear, the dart, or the javelin (<em>hassegah &rsquo;alav herev uvlo taqum hanit masse uveshiryah</em>). The list of weapons &mdash; <em>herev</em> (sword), <em>hanit</em> (spear), <em>masse</em> (dart/throwing weapon), <em>shiriyon</em> (or <em>shiriyan</em>, the javelin used as shorthand for weapon) &mdash; covers the full range of ancient infantry and cavalry weapons. The systematic ineffectiveness of each weapon category against Leviathan establishes that the chaos-monster cannot be defeated by any human weapons system. This impossibility-catalog is the creature-level analog to YHWH&rsquo;s challenge in 40:9&ndash;14: can you arm yourself like God? The answer for Leviathan combat: no.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Leviathan counting iron as straw (<em>yaheshov barzel leteven</em>) and bronze as rotten wood (<em>unehoshet ke&rsquo;ets meraqav</em>) inverts the materials hierarchy of ancient military technology. Iron was the hardest known metal and the basis of Iron Age military superiority; bronze was the second-hardest. The materials hierarchy for weapons: iron &gt; bronze &gt; wood &gt; straw. Leviathan&rsquo;s evaluation reverses this: what human military technology prizes as invincible (iron), Leviathan dismisses as straw; what it prizes as strong (bronze), Leviathan sees as rotten wood. The chaos-dragon exists in a materials register where the entirety of human weapons technology is worthless.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The arrow not making Leviathan flee (<em>lo-yanisenu ben qashat</em>), sling-stones being turned to stubble (<em>kalal nehepekhu lo avanot qela&rsquo;</em>), and the club counted as stubble (<em>kehakash neheshav totah</em>) continues the weapons-futility catalog. The arrow was the longest-range ancient weapon and the primary threat to cavalry; the sling was David&rsquo;s weapon against Goliath (1 Sam 17:40). The progressive futility from close-range (sword, spear, v26) to mid-range (javelin) to long-range (arrow, sling) exhausts the full spectrum of ancient weapons range. No weapon system in the ancient world&rsquo;s arsenal touches Leviathan.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Clubs (<em>totah</em>) being counted as stubble and Leviathan laughing at the rattle of javelins (<em>yiskhaq leshe&rsquo;on kidon</em>) returns to the laughing (<em>sahaq</em>) vocabulary used for the wild donkey (39:7) and the horse (39:22: laughing at fear). The laughing animal/creature that finds dangerous things harmless is the divine speeches&rsquo; image for the creature that operates in a register beyond ordinary threat-response. The war horse laughs at battle because it is trained beyond ordinary horse-psychology; Leviathan laughs at weapons because it exists beyond ordinary physical vulnerability. Both express a designed capacity that exceeds the typical creaturely response to danger.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Leviathan&rsquo;s underparts being like sharp potsherds (<em>tahtav hadudey heres</em>), spreading the threshing sledge upon the mud (<em>yirpa haruts &rsquo;al tit</em>) describes the creature&rsquo;s underside as offensive-weapon in itself. The threshing sledge (<em>moreg</em> / <em>haruts</em>) was a wooden board with flint or iron teeth on its underside, dragged by oxen over harvested grain to thresh it (Isa 41:15: &ldquo;I will make of you a threshing sledge&rdquo;). Leviathan&rsquo;s underside is a living threshing sledge: as it moves through the water or across the mud, it threshes what is beneath it. The chaos-dragon is simultaneously armored above and weaponized below.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Leviathan making the deep boil like a pot (<em>yarehash metsulah kayir</em>) and the sea like a pot of ointment (<em>veyasem yam kamarqahah</em>) uses the boiling-liquid imagery for the turbulence created by the chaos-monster&rsquo;s movement through water. In Mesopotamian creation mythology, Tiamat is the salt sea; Marduk&rsquo;s combat with Tiamat disturbs the primordial waters to their depths. In the Ugaritic Baal cycle, Yam&rsquo;s/Lotan&rsquo;s presence churns the sea. YHWH&rsquo;s description of Leviathan&rsquo;s motion making the deep boil describes the visible effect on the sea of the chaos-creature&rsquo;s movement: the surface of the sea betrays what moves in its depths.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Leviathan making the path behind him shine (<em>ahar yair netiv</em>) and the deep look hoary/white-haired (<em>yehashev tehom leseyvah</em>) describes the wake phenomenon. A large body moving at speed through water creates a white-water wake; the deep that looks hoary/white-haired is the foam-and-turbulence of the monster&rsquo;s passage. In ancient Mediterranean seafaring, a ship&rsquo;s wake was a visible trail; the cosmic scale of Leviathan&rsquo;s wake &mdash; making the entire deep look like a white-haired elder &mdash; describes a disturbance of cosmic proportions. The comparison to an elder&rsquo;s white hair uses the ANE symbol of wisdom and longevity for the disturbed sea-surface.</p>",
    "33": "<p>&ldquo;On earth there is not his like (<em>eyn &rsquo;alav mashel ba&rsquo;aretz</em>), a creature without fear&rdquo; &mdash; the declaration of Leviathan&rsquo;s uniqueness on earth establishes his status as sui generis: beyond comparison, without a category. In ANE taxonomy, things were understood through comparison and category (in Mesopotamian wisdom lists, the <em>Urra-hubullu</em> tablets organized all known things into categories); the thing that has no <em>mashel</em> (comparison/equal) is outside the taxonomic system. Leviathan is the creature for whom no comparison exists on earth &mdash; a creature outside the normal system of creaturely knowledge and categorization.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The closing declaration &mdash; &ldquo;He sees every high thing (<em>kol-gavoha yir&rsquo;eh</em>); he is king over all the sons of pride (<em>melek &rsquo;al-kol-benei shahats</em>)&rdquo; &mdash; gives Leviathan a cosmic dominion. The &ldquo;sons of pride/arrogance&rdquo; (<em>benei shahats</em>) may refer to the proud animals described in the divine speeches (the wild donkey, the wild ox, the war horse &mdash; all creatures that exemplify non-submission to human control) or to the proud among humanity. Leviathan as king over all pride locates the chaos-monster at the apex of non-submission to human order. YHWH&rsquo;s point: you, Job, who have contended with me &mdash; you are one of the sons of pride over whom Leviathan is king; and even Leviathan is subject to me, who made him. The argument comes full circle.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'job')
    merge_comm(existing, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'job', existing)
    total = sum(len(vv) for vv in CONTEXT.values())
    parts = ', '.join(f'ch{ch}={len(CONTEXT[ch])}' for ch in sorted(CONTEXT, key=int))
    print(f'Job 39-41 mkt-context: {total} verses written ({parts}).')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
